{"title_page": "Talia (given name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox given name\n| name          = Talia\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| pronunciation = \n| gender        = Female\n| meaning       = \"dew of [[God]]\", \"lamb\", \"to [[wikt:bloom|bloom]]\", \"to recite\"\n| region        = [[Mediterranean]]\n| language      = Arabic, Assyrian, Hebrew, Greek\n| origin        = \n| alternative spelling = Taliah, Taaliah\n| nickname      = \n| variant forms = \n| related names = \n| name day      = \n| derived       = \n| popularity    = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Talia''' (Hebrew: \u05d8\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4 \"Dew of God\") is a feminine given name. Alternative spellings include: '''Taliah''', '''Taaliah''', '''Talya''', '''Tahlia''', '''Taliya''' or '''Taylia'''. \n\nThe name '''Talia''' bears phonological similarities to names found in many languages. The [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] community heavily used the name \"T(h)alia\", which, in [[Neo-Aramaic]], means \"boy\".<ref>http://www.assyrianlanguages.org/sureth/dosearch.php?searchkey=5137&language=id</ref> The Greek name [[Thalia (disambiguation)|Thalia]] (or '''Thal\u00eda''' or '''Thaleia''' ({{IPAc-en|\u03b8|\u0259|\u02c8|l|a\u026a|.|\u0259}}; Greek: ''\u0398\u03ac\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1'' from ''\u03b8\u03ac\u03bb\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd'' \"to bloom\") dates back to antiquity and is relatively popular in a number of countries. However, pronunciation varies and in some cases the \u03b8/t distinction of the original Greek is lost (e.g. {{IPA-es|ta\u02c8li.a}}). A similar-sounding name is also in use in [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] cultures.\n\n==List of people with the given name Talia==\n* [[Talia Balsam]], actress\n* [[Talia Madison]], the ring name of female wrestler Jamie Szantyr, more commonly known as Velvet Sky\n* [[Talia Shire]], actress\n* [[Talia Castellano]], internet celebrity and honorary covergirl\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Queen Talia]], a character from the video game ''Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic''\n* [[Sun, Moon, and Talia|Talia]], the name of the dormant princess in an early version of the ''Sleeping Beauty'' legend\n* [[Talia al Ghul]], a character from DC Comics.\n* [[Talia Gladys]], a fictional character in ''Mobile Suit Gundam SEED Destiny''\n* [[Talia Sahid]], a character on the American daytime drama ''One Life to Live''\n* [[Talia Winters]], a character from ''Babylon 5''\n* [[Talia Wagner]], daughter of Nightcrawler and The Scarlet Witch in an alternate universe of X-Men\n* [[Talia Hale]], Mother of Derek Hale in Teen Wolf.\n*Talia Parra, the titular character of [[Talia in the Kitchen]]\n\ntahlia is a sick bittie\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Australian given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name          = Talia\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| pronunciation = \n| gender        = Female\n| meaning       = \"dew of [[God]]\", \"lamb\", \"to [[wikt:bloom|bloom]]\", \"to recite\"\n| region        = [[Mediterranean]]\n| language      = Arabic, Assyrian, Hebrew, Greek\n| origin        = \n| alternative spelling = Taliah, Taaliah\n| nickname      = \n| variant forms = \n| related names = \n| name day      = \n| derived       = \n| popularity    = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Talia''' (Hebrew: \u05d8\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4 \"Dew of God\") is a feminine given name. Alternative spellings include: '''Taliah''', '''Taaliah''', '''Talya''', '''Tahlia''', '''Taliya''' or '''Taylia'''. \n\nThe name '''Talia''' bears phonological similarities to names found in many languages. The [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] community heavily used the name \"T(h)alia\", which, in [[Neo-Aramaic]], means \"boy\".<ref>http://www.assyrianlanguages.org/sureth/dosearch.php?searchkey=5137&language=id</ref> The Greek name [[Thalia (disambiguation)|Thalia]] (or '''Thal\u00eda''' or '''Thaleia''' ({{IPAc-en|\u03b8|\u0259|\u02c8|l|a\u026a|.|\u0259}}; Greek: ''\u0398\u03ac\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1'' from ''\u03b8\u03ac\u03bb\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd'' \"to bloom\") dates back to antiquity and is relatively popular in a number of countries. However, pronunciation varies and in some cases the \u03b8/t distinction of the original Greek is lost (e.g. {{IPA-es|ta\u02c8li.a}}). A similar-sounding name is also in use in [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] cultures.\n\n==List of people with the given name Talia==\n* [[Talia Balsam]], actress\n* [[Talia Madison]], the ring name of female wrestler Jamie Szantyr, more commonly known as Velvet Sky\n* [[Talia Shire]], actress\n* [[Talia Castellano]], internet celebrity and honorary covergirl\n\n===Fictional characters===\n* [[Queen Talia]], a character from the video game ''Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic''\n* [[Sun, Moon, and Talia|Talia]], the name of the dormant princess in an early version of the ''Sleeping Beauty'' legend\n* [[Talia al Ghul]], a character from DC Comics.\n* [[Talia Gladys]], a fictional character in ''Mobile Suit Gundam SEED Destiny''\n* [[Talia Sahid]], a character on the American daytime drama ''One Life to Live''\n* [[Talia Winters]], a character from ''Babylon 5''\n* [[Talia Wagner]], daughter of Nightcrawler and The Scarlet Witch in an alternate universe of X-Men\n* [[Talia Hale]], Mother of Derek Hale in Teen Wolf.\n*Talia Parra, the titular character of [[Talia in the Kitchen]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Talia (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Thalia (disambiguation)|Thalia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:Australian given names]]\n", "name_user": "1.129.109.219", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talia_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "LGBT Activism in Iraq", "text_new": "'''Iraqi Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Trans (LGBT) activism''' refers to any work done to advance the state of LGBT peoples in political, cultural, or home safety. The [[Iraq]] government has maintained an anti-LGBT stance since gaining independence in 1932 where homosexuality was officially banned.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qmuqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT186&lpg=PT186&dq=IRCC+resolution+234#v=onepage&q=IRCC%20resolution%20234&f=false|title=A Scientific Aspect of Transgenders|last=TARAFDER|first=AJAY MAJUMDER, RABIN|date=2019-08-21|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=9781645875659}}</ref> This would be expanded in the IRCC Resolution 234 of 2001 which would punish sodomy, or any homosexual act, with the death penalty.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to harsh stigma against people who are LGBT, many activist organizations find themselves at a crossroads of whether to focus on building tolerance in Iraq, or instead focusing on ensuring safety or asylum for the LGBT communities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=Lauren|date=2014-05-01|title=Academics and activism : a comparative study of contemporary historical writings on same-sex sexuality and LGBT activists in the Middle East.|url=https://ir.library.louisville.edu/etd/276|journal=Electronic Theses and Dissertations|doi=10.18297/etd/276|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===[[Kingdom of Iraq]]===\nOn October 3, 1932 Britain granted Iraq independence, and one of the first laws that passed was the banning of homosexuality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Republic and [[Ba'athist Iraq]]===\nIn 1958, The [[14 July Revolution]], known as the 1958 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat, brought an end to a monarchy and established a brand new government.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=The Middle East and Early Modern Europe|date=2016-05-23|pages=54\u201370|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315508252|doi=10.4324/9781315508252-4|title=The Middle East in Modern World History}}</ref> During this regime, LGBT people found a new voice, and greater visibility of LGBT people were making it into the mainstream culture. This is seen most in Baghdad between the end of the Iran-Iraq War in 1988 and the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in August 1990, where scenes depicting gay men became more affluent,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Rohde|first=Achim|date=2016-11-01|title=Gays, Cross-Dressers, and EmosNonnormative Masculinities in Militarized Iraq|journal=Journal of Middle East Women's Studies|volume=12|issue=3|pages=433\u2013449|doi=10.1215/15525864-3637642|issn=1552-5864}}</ref> as well as female hormones being freely available in many Iraqi pharmacies.<ref>{{Citation|last=Shortland|first=Anja|chapter=Trading with Kidnappers|date=2019-01-24|pages=149\u2013164|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198815471|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198815471.003.0008|title=Kidnap}}</ref>\n\nThis increase in freedoms would slowly begin to fade late into the [[Saddam Hussein|Saddam]] regime as he gained more power over the Iraq government. A cultural shift started to form, with an emphasis on conservative values that glorified military action, and masculinity. There has been no evidence of organized violence against LGBT people before 2003.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== 2003\u20132007 ===\nStarting in 2003, a large spike in Anti-LGBT violence can be seen, with many people outside of the LGBT community, ranging from journalist, citizens, and even some politicians in Iraq, reporting how brutal many of the attacks were.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Symposium volume : gender on the frontiers : confronting intersectionalities.|last=Columbia University. School of Law.|oclc=800741178}}</ref> It is around this time that many LGBT activist organizations, such as The Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq and Iraqi LGBT, started to form in response to the growing violence. The largest amounts of murder and death would happen during this time period, and despite the formation of many LGBT activist organization, many would be forced to disband, go underground, or travel to different countries to continue work there.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=KADHUM|first=OULA|date=2018-12-12|title=Ethno\u2010sectarianism in Iraq, diaspora positionality and political transnationalism|journal=Global Networks|doi=10.1111/glob.12222|issn=1470-2266}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008\u2013Present ===\nThe war's end in 2008, saw a decrease in violence for people's daily lives, and this allowed a surge in nightlife, including gay nightlife, in Baghdad, Basra, Najaf, and other cities for people in the LGBT community.<ref name=\":1\" /> This, however, also came with sadrist militiamen, part of the Mahdi Army, to reposition themselves to killing people who identify as homosexual.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAccording to a ''New York Times'' story in April 2009, Shi\u02bfi clerics in Baghdad \"devoted a portion of Friday Prayer services to inveighing against homosexuality.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> This emboldened many a people, and saw that the increase of LGBT activity, slowed down significantly.\n\nEarly 2012 saw the saw a large wave of killings done to \"emo\" people, and would later be called the [[Emo killings in Iraq|\"Emo Killings\"]]. These killings were done by Mahdi Army, and were largely criticized as needless acts of violence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Many Shi'i clerics, as well as the chairperson of the human rights committee of the Iraqi parliament, denounced these killings, though were also against emo culture as a whole.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Current Activist Organization ==\n\n===[[Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq|The Organization of Women\u2019s Freedom in Iraq (OWFI)]]===\nThe OWFI started in 2003 and has a focus on ensuring pioneering work to rebuild Iraq with secular democracy and human rights for all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madre.org/partners/organization-womens-freedom-iraq|title=Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq|website=MADRE|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Following the battles for Mosul and other nearby cities against ISIS, over 3 million people have found themselves displaced, with 10 million needing humanitarian aid,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|title=OCHA \u2014 United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|doi = 10.1163/_afco_asc_2528}}</ref> OWFI spearheaded an organized effort to change Iraq's Anti-Shelter Policy, which only allowed government run shelters to exist. OWFI led over 40 different local organization to change these policies, and expand the basic civil liberties of people in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=Lisa|date=2017|title=Countering Iraq's Anti-Shelter Policy in the Islamic State Era|doi=10.2139/ssrn.3185731|issn=1556-5068}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraqueer ===\nIraqueer formed in March 2015 with LGBT+ members all over Iraq, with the express goal of raising the awareness level among and about LGBT+ identities in the Iraqi society, and to advocate for LGBT+ rights in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqueer.org/about.html|title=About|website=IraQueer|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> Iraqueer has three main methods of achieving its goal, by providing education, advocacy, and direct services. In terms of education, Iraqueer has published several guides ranging from security to health safety along with the novel <u>Living in The Margins,</u> containing LGBT stories from people living in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqueer.org/publications.html|title=Publications|website=IraQueer|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> They also upload videos to YouTube that talk about the different aspects of being an LGBT individual in Iraq. Finally, they host several workshops dedicated to teaching people about gender and sexuality, how to lobby and properly advocate, and to maintain safety and security in times of crisis. Iraqueer has submitted several reports international bodies, including the United Nations, talking about the state of LGBT people in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=CRC Discrimination Based on Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity and Violence against Girls|doi = 10.1163/2210-7975_hrd-3601-2016011}}</ref> Lastly, Iraqueer maintains safe houses in Iraq for LGBT people seeking safety or asylum.\n\n=== Iraqi LGBT ===\nIraqi LGBT is a LGBT rights organization, establish in September 2005, that was created in response to the rise in violence against LGBT people.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqilgbt.org.uk/|title=Iraqi LGBT \u2013 Everything You Need To Know|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Their main goal is the creation and maintenance of several different \"safe houses\" in Iraq, where people who are fleeing from prosecution can find protection and safety.<ref name=\":2\" /> Though they have done activist work promoting tolerance in Iraq, Iraqi LGBT focuses on relocating LGBT people to safer countries, and providing legal help for the LGBT people seeking asylum.\n\n=== International Railroad for Queer Refugees ===\nFounded in 2008, International Railroad for Queer Refugees (IRQR)  provides financial and resettlement assistance for LGBT asylum seekers who are fleeing their homes because of prosecution for their sexual orientation, or gender identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irqr.net/|title=IRQR|website=International Railroad for Queer Refugees\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0646\u0627\u0647\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> They also provide assistance and workshops for local organizations, so they can be better prepared in dealing with legal and social ramifications, as well as maintaining a network with different organizations so information can be spread easily, and not be intercepted by government officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irqr.net/?page_id=6693|title=Programs and Projects|website=International Railroad for Queer Refugees\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0646\u0627\u0647\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n== National Backlash ==\nStarting in 2003 with the rise of religious conservatism in the Iraq government, many media outlets began to publish articles and think pieces that condemned queer and LGBT people as practices of Satanism that contradict Islamic precepts and human nature.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Homosexuality in the Middle East: an analysis of dominant and competitive discourses|last=Tolino, Serena|date=2014|publisher=Universit\u00e0 Ca\u2019 Foscari|oclc=1030047472}}</ref> Major killings that targeted LGBT people began during this time, though the killings done in 2004 would not be discovered until later on due to the large amount of violence already occurring in the region. The people responsible for the killings would be linked to the Iran-backed Badr Corps, which form part of the Islamic Supreme Council of Iraq (ISCI).<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1962|title=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development|journal=International Organization|volume=16|issue=1|pages=218\u2013223|doi=10.1017/s0020818300010869|issn=0020-8183}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, on Grand Ayatollah Ali al-Sistani's website, a [[fatwa]], or a ruling on a point of Islamic law, was issued that declared the killing of homosexual men justified. It would be later taken down due to protests by advocate groups.<ref>{{Citation|last=Torcetti|first=Shelley|chapter=Living in the shadows|date=2019-07-17|pages=1\u201343|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780429265488|doi=10.4324/9780429265488-1|title=Living in the Shadows of China's HIV/AIDS Epidemics}}</ref> Many international viewers saw this as one main causes in the rise of anti-LGBT violence, the [[Human Rights Watch]] saw little correlation between the fatwa and the violence.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Mahdi Army formed again in 2009, and using the LGBT community as proof that the militia is needed to cleanse Iraq of undesirable people. The method used most often to succeed in their goals was to kill LGBT people. This would go on to be known as the killing campaigns.<ref name=\":3\" /> The militia justified their actions by citing that the killings were done for a moral cause that was meant to protect masculinity and traditional values.<ref name=\":3\" /> During the height of these killings, magazines and newspapers like ''Al-Esbuyia'' and ''Al-Sabah'' would publish pieces that supported the killings, and called for more action to stop the \"feminization of men\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== International Intervention ==\n\n=== International Law ===\nIn 1971, Iraq ratified the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] (ICCPR) treaty, which placed a mandate on Iraqi officials to act against actions done to antagonize or oppress protected and minority groups,<ref>{{Citation|last=Christian|first=Tomuschat|title=International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (1966)|date=October 2010|encyclopedia=Max Planck Encyclopedia of Public International Law|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199231690}}</ref> among these civil and political rights include; ''The Right to Life and Security, Protection Against Torture and Inhuman and Degrading Treatment,'' and ''The Guarantee of Non-Discrimination''. Iraq has continuously violated these rights, and although the [[United Nations Human Rights Committee|UN Human Rights Committee]] has condemned Iraq for violating the treaty, it has not faced any major consequences because of it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=\"They want us exterminated\" : murder, torture, sexual orientation and gender in Iraq|last=Long, Scott.|date=2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1564325242|oclc=931791278}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT in Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Iraqi Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Trans (LGBT) activism''' refers to any work done to advance the state of LGBT peoples in political, cultural, or home safety. The [[Iraq]] government has maintained an anti-LGBT stance since gaining independence in 1932 where homosexuality was officially banned.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qmuqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT186&lpg=PT186&dq=IRCC+resolution+234#v=onepage&q=IRCC%20resolution%20234&f=false|title=A Scientific Aspect of Transgenders|last=TARAFDER|first=AJAY MAJUMDER, RABIN|date=2019-08-21|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=9781645875659}}</ref> This would be expanded in the IRCC Resolution 234 of 2001 which would punish sodomy, or any homosexual act, with the death penalty.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to harsh stigma against people who are LGBT, many activist organizations find themselves at a crossroads of whether to focus on building tolerance in Iraq, or instead focusing on ensuring safety or asylum for the LGBT communities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=Lauren|date=2014-05-01|title=Academics and activism : a comparative study of contemporary historical writings on same-sex sexuality and LGBT activists in the Middle East.|url=https://ir.library.louisville.edu/etd/276|journal=Electronic Theses and Dissertations|doi=10.18297/etd/276|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===[[Kingdom of Iraq]]===\nOn October 3, 1932 Britain granted Iraq independence, and one of the first laws that passed was the banning of homosexuality.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Republic and [[Ba'athist Iraq]]===\nIn 1958, The [[14 July Revolution]], known as the 1958 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat, brought an end to a monarchy and established a brand new government.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=The Middle East and Early Modern Europe|date=2016-05-23|pages=54\u201370|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315508252|doi=10.4324/9781315508252-4|title=The Middle East in Modern World History}}</ref> During this regime, LGBT people found a new voice, and greater visibility of LGBT people were making it into the mainstream culture. This is seen most in Baghdad between the end of the Iran-Iraq War in 1988 and the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in August 1990, where scenes depicting gay men became more affluent,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Rohde|first=Achim|date=2016-11-01|title=Gays, Cross-Dressers, and EmosNonnormative Masculinities in Militarized Iraq|journal=Journal of Middle East Women's Studies|volume=12|issue=3|pages=433\u2013449|doi=10.1215/15525864-3637642|issn=1552-5864}}</ref> as well as female hormones being freely available in many Iraqi pharmacies.<ref>{{Citation|last=Shortland|first=Anja|chapter=Trading with Kidnappers|date=2019-01-24|pages=149\u2013164|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198815471|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198815471.003.0008|title=Kidnap}}</ref>\n\nThis increase in freedoms would slowly begin to fade late into the [[Saddam Hussein|Saddam]] regime as he gained more power over the Iraq government. A cultural shift started to form, with an emphasis on conservative values that glorified military action, and masculinity. There has been no evidence of organized violence against LGBT people before 2003.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== 2003\u20132007 ===\nStarting in 2003, a large spike in Anti-LGBT violence can be seen, with many people outside of the LGBT community, ranging from journalist, citizens, and even some politicians in Iraq, reporting how brutal many of the attacks were.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Symposium volume : gender on the frontiers : confronting intersectionalities.|last=Columbia University. School of Law.|oclc=800741178}}</ref> It is around this time that many LGBT activist organizations, such as The Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq and Iraqi LGBT, started to form in response to the growing violence. The largest amounts of murder and death would happen during this time period, and despite the formation of many LGBT activist organization, many would be forced to disband, go underground, or travel to different countries to continue work there.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=KADHUM|first=OULA|date=2018-12-12|title=Ethno\u2010sectarianism in Iraq, diaspora positionality and political transnationalism|journal=Global Networks|doi=10.1111/glob.12222|issn=1470-2266}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008\u2013Present ===\nThe war's end in 2008, saw a decrease in violence for people's daily lives, and this allowed a surge in nightlife, including gay nightlife, in Baghdad, Basra, Najaf, and other cities for people in the LGBT community.<ref name=\":1\" /> This, however, also came with sadrist militiamen, part of the Mahdi Army, to reposition themselves to killing people who identify as homosexual.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nAccording to a ''New York Times'' story in April 2009, Shi\u02bfi clerics in Baghdad \"devoted a portion of Friday Prayer services to inveighing against homosexuality.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> This emboldened many a people, and saw that the increase of LGBT activity, slowed down significantly. \n\nEarly 2012 saw the saw a large wave of killings done to \"emo\" people, and would later be called the [[Emo killings in Iraq|\"Emo Killings\"]]. These killings were done by Mahdi Army, and were largely criticized as needless acts of violence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Many Shi'i clerics, as well as the chairperson of the human rights committee of the Iraqi parliament, denounced these killings, though were also against emo culture as a whole.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Current Activist Organization ==\n\n===[[Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq|The Organization of Women\u2019s Freedom in Iraq (OWFI)]]===\nThe OWFI started in 2003 and has a focus on ensuring pioneering work to rebuild Iraq with secular democracy and human rights for all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.madre.org/partners/organization-womens-freedom-iraq|title=Organization of Women's Freedom in Iraq|website=MADRE|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Following the battles for Mosul and other nearby cities against ISIS, over 3 million people have found themselves displaced, with 10 million needing humanitarian aid,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|title=OCHA \u2014 United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|doi = 10.1163/_afco_asc_2528}}</ref> OWFI spearheaded an organized effort to change Iraq's Anti-Shelter Policy, which only allowed government run shelters to exist. OWFI led over 40 different local organization to change these policies, and expand the basic civil liberties of people in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=Lisa|date=2017|title=Countering Iraq's Anti-Shelter Policy in the Islamic State Era|doi=10.2139/ssrn.3185731|issn=1556-5068}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraqueer ===\nIraqueer formed in March 2015 with LGBT+ members all over Iraq, with the express goal of raising the awareness level among and about LGBT+ identities in the Iraqi society, and to advocate for LGBT+ rights in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqueer.org/about.html|title=About|website=IraQueer|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> Iraqueer has three main methods of achieving its goal, by providing education, advocacy, and direct services. In terms of education, Iraqueer has published several guides ranging from security to health safety along with the novel <u>Living in The Margins,</u> containing LGBT stories from people living in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqueer.org/publications.html|title=Publications|website=IraQueer|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> They also upload videos to YouTube that talk about the different aspects of being an LGBT individual in Iraq. Finally, they host several workshops dedicated to teaching people about gender and sexuality, how to lobby and properly advocate, and to maintain safety and security in times of crisis. Iraqueer has submitted several reports international bodies, including the United Nations, talking about the state of LGBT people in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=CRC Discrimination Based on Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity and Violence against Girls|doi = 10.1163/2210-7975_hrd-3601-2016011}}</ref> Lastly, Iraqueer maintains safe houses in Iraq for LGBT people seeking safety or asylum. \n\n=== Iraqi LGBT ===\nIraqi LGBT is a LGBT rights organization, establish in September 2005, that was created in response to the rise in violence against LGBT people.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqilgbt.org.uk/|title=Iraqi LGBT \u2013 Everything You Need To Know|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Their main goal is the creation and maintenance of several different \"safe houses\" in Iraq, where people who are fleeing from prosecution can find protection and safety.<ref name=\":2\" /> Though they have done activist work promoting tolerance in Iraq, Iraqi LGBT focuses on relocating LGBT people to safer countries, and providing legal help for the LGBT people seeking asylum. \n\n=== International Railroad for Queer Refugees ===\nFounded in 2008, International Railroad for Queer Refugees (IRQR)  provides financial and resettlement assistance for LGBT asylum seekers who are fleeing their homes because of prosecution for their sexual orientation, or gender identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irqr.net/|title=IRQR|website=International Railroad for Queer Refugees\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0646\u0627\u0647\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> They also provide assistance and workshops for local organizations, so they can be better prepared in dealing with legal and social ramifications, as well as maintaining a network with different organizations so information can be spread easily, and not be intercepted by government officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irqr.net/?page_id=6693|title=Programs and Projects|website=International Railroad for Queer Refugees\u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u067e\u0646\u0627\u0647\u062c\u0648\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n== National Backlash ==\nStarting in 2003 with the rise of religious conservatism in the Iraq government, many media outlets began to publish articles and think pieces that condemned queer and LGBT people as practices of Satanism that contradict Islamic precepts and human nature.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Homosexuality in the Middle East: an analysis of dominant and competitive discourses|last=Tolino, Serena|date=2014|publisher=Universit\u00e0 Ca\u2019 Foscari|oclc=1030047472}}</ref> Major killings that targeted LGBT people began during this time, though the killings done in 2004 wouldn't be discovered until later on due to the large amount of violence already occurring in the region. The people responsible for the killings would be linked to the Iran-backed Badr Corps, which form part of the Islamic Supreme Council of Iraq (ISCI).<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1962|title=International Bank for Reconstruction and Development|journal=International Organization|volume=16|issue=1|pages=218\u2013223|doi=10.1017/s0020818300010869|issn=0020-8183}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, on Grand Ayatollah Ali al-Sistani\u2019s website, a [[fatwa]], or a ruling on a point of Islamic law, was issued that declared the killing of homosexual men justified. It would be later taken down due to protests by advocate groups.<ref>{{Citation|last=Torcetti|first=Shelley|chapter=Living in the shadows|date=2019-07-17|pages=1\u201343|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780429265488|doi=10.4324/9780429265488-1|title=Living in the Shadows of China's HIV/AIDS Epidemics}}</ref> Many international viewers saw this as one main causes in the rise of anti-LGBT violence, the [[Human Rights Watch]] saw little correlation between the fatwa and the violence.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Mahdi Army formed again in 2009, and using the LGBT community as proof that the militia is needed to cleanse Iraq of undesirable people. The method used most often to succeed in their goals was to kill LGBT people. This would go on to be known as the killing campaigns.<ref name=\":3\" /> The militia justified their actions by citing that the killings were done for a moral cause that was meant to protect masculinity and traditional values.<ref name=\":3\" /> During the height of these killings, magazines and newspapers like ''Al-Esbuyia'' and ''Al-Sabah'' would publish pieces that supported the killings, and called for more action to stop the \"feminization of men\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== International Intervention ==\n\n=== International Law ===\nIn 1971, Iraq ratified the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] (ICCPR) treaty, which placed a mandate on Iraqi officials to act against actions done to antagonize or oppress protected and minority groups,<ref>{{Citation|last=Christian|first=Tomuschat|title=International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (1966)|date=October 2010|encyclopedia=Max Planck Encyclopedia of Public International Law|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199231690}}</ref> among these civil and political rights include; ''The Right to Life and Security, Protection Against Torture and Inhuman and Degrading Treatment,'' and ''The Guarantee of Non-Discrimination''. Iraq has continuously violated these rights, and although the [[United Nations Human Rights Committee|UN Human Rights Committee]] has condemned Iraq for violating the treaty, it has not faced any major consequences because of it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=\"They want us exterminated\" : murder, torture, sexual orientation and gender in Iraq|last=Long, Scott.|date=2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-1564325242|oclc=931791278}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:LGBT in Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: wouldn't \u2192 would not,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_Activism_in_Iraq"}
{"title_page": "List of New Jersey tornadoes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\nThis is a list of all [[tornado]]es reported in the U.S. state of [[New Jersey]].\n\n==Tornadoes==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Date\n!EF#\n!Location\n!Description\n|-\n|April 21, 2020\n|EF0\n|[[Mantoloking, New Jersey|Normandy Beach]], NJ\n|A waterspout formed over Barnegat Bay between Silver Bay and Kettle Creek, then moved ashore at the Normandy Beach Yacht Club. Several boats and associated trailers were tossed and flipped, with minor damage being reported to at least one home on South Court. This weak tornado may have lifted as it proceeded east across Route 35, and approached the coast just north of Normandy Shores Beach Club. The tornado then became a waterspout as it emerged over the coastal waters, causing little or no additional damage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=202004232002-KPHI-NOUS41-PNSPHI|title=NWSChat - NOAA's National Weather Service}}</ref>\n|-\n|November 1, 2019\n|EF1\n|[[Harding Township, New Jersey|Harding Township]]-[[Florham Park Borough, New Jersey|Florham Park Borough]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down in Harding Township, traveling through [[Chatham Township, New Jersey|Chatham]], [[Madison Borough, New Jersey|Madison]], before ending in Florham Park. This storm uprooted several trees and power lines, some of which fell onto residential homes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/total_forecast/getprod.php?new&prod=XXXPNSPHI&wfo=phi|title=NWSChat - NOAA's National Weather Service|last=Service|first=NOAA's National Weather|website=nwschat.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=A tornado caused the Halloween storm damage in northern N.J., weather service says|url=https://www.nj.com/weather/2019/11/a-tornado-caused-the-halloween-storm-damage-in-northern-nj-weather-service-says.html|website=nj.com|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 7, 2019\n|EF0\n|[[Millville, New Jersey|Millville]], NJ\n|A weak tornado briefly touched down in a field of solar panels near the Millville City Sewer Department Facility, destroying several rows of panels. The tornado then moved into a wooded area, snapping one tree and damaging several others, dissipating shortly after.<ref name=\"Service\">{{Cite web|url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201908102018-KPHI-NOUS41-PNSPHI|title=NWSChat - NOAA's National Weather Service|last=Service|first=NOAA's National Weather|website=nwschat.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 7, 2019\n|EF0\n|[[Hightstown, New Jersey|Hightstown]], NJ\n|A weak tornado briefly touched down on the property of a greenhouse in Hightstown, shattering the glass roof, blowing shards of glass hundreds of yards away, piercing the doors and walls of a nearby barn. Several metal support beams from the greenhouse were tossed up to 200 yards as well. The tornado then passed over an barn, scattering glass, flower planters and support beams into an nearby field. Several trees were downed. The tornado dissipated as it moved into a clearing outside of the wooded area.<ref name=\"Service\"/>\n|-\n|August 7, 2019\n|EF0\n|[[Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey|Springfield]], NJ\n|A tornado briefly touched down near Springfield Avenue and Route 22, downing power lines, busting solar panels and damaging dozens of vehicles at an dealership. An rooftop air conditioning unit collapsed onto an sedan, and a section of the dealership's warehouse roof was torn wide open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2019/08/07/tornado-touched-down-in-springfield-nj/|title=Tornado touched down in Springfield, NJ|last=Chasan|first=Aliza|date=August 7, 2019|website=Pix 11|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|July 11, 2019\n|EF1\n|[[Mount Laurel, New Jersey|Mount Laurel]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down in an open area on an golf course in Mount Laurel, travelling discontinuously for more than an mile, snapping and uprooting numerous trees, and damaging several apartment buildings before dissipating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/weather/2019/07/tornado-confirmed-during-fierce-thunderstorms-in-nj-that-makes-5-tornadoes-already-this-year.html|title=Tornado confirmed during fierce thunderstorms in N.J. That makes 5 tornadoes already this year.|last=Melisurgo|first=Len|date=July 12, 2019|website=NJ.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|July 6, 2019\n|EF0\n|Mount Laurel, NJ\n|A tornado briefly touched down in a warehouse parking lot, overturning a car before passing over the warehouse, causing minor roof damage before dissipating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://6abc.com/weather/natl-weather-service-confirms-tornado-touched-down-in-mt-laurel/5382142/|title=National Weather Service confirms tornado touched down in Mt. Laurel|last=|first=|date=July 6, 2019|website=WPVI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n|-\n|June 13, 2019\n|EF0\n|[[Mullica Hill, New Jersey|Mullica Hill]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down near Saddle Court in Mullica Hill, ripping a gutter off an residence and lifting backyard furniture approximately 50 yards. The tornado then moved northeast, damaging several trees before dissipating southwest of Highway 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/news/2019/06/13/tornado-mullica-hill-gloucester-county-nj/1452247001/|title=Two tornadoes confirmed in South Jersey, National Weather Service says|last=Berkery|first=Sheri|date=June 13, 2019|website=Cherry Hill Courier-Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201906142039-KPHI-NOUS41-PNSPHI|title=NWSChat - NOAA's National Weather Service|last=Service|first=NOAA's National Weather|website=nwschat.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 13, 2019\n|EF1\n|[[Deptford Township, New Jersey|Deptford]]-[[Blackwood, New Jersey|Blackwood]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down near Deptford, snapping and uprooting several trees and damaging three residences. The tornado then moved into Blackwood, where an apartment building was damaged by an uprooted tree.<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|May 28, 2019\n|EF1\n|[[Stanhope, New Jersey|Stanhope]]-[[Hopatcong, New Jersey|Hopatcong]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down in Stanhope, damaging an high school before moving into Hopatcong, downing trees and power lines before disspiating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njherald.com/news/20190529/tornado-touchdown-confirmed-in-stanhope-classified-as-ef1|title=Tornado touchdown confirmed in Stanhope, classified as EF1|last=Miller|first=Jennifer Jean|website=New Jersey Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 24, 2017\n|EF0\n|[[Howell Township, New Jersey|Howell]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down near Oak Glen Park in Howell, uprooting numerous hardwood trees before dissipating.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-jersey/howell/nws-investigating-possible-tornado-howell-police-say-video|title=NWS Confirms 2 Tornadoes In Howell: See The Video|date=2017-06-24|website=Howell, NJ Patch|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 24, 2017\n|EF0\n|Howell, NJ\n|A tornado touched down in the parking lot of [[The Home Depot|Home Depot]] in Howell, just a few minutes after the Oak Glen Park tornado dissipated. Several trees were uprooted and snapped, and metal roofing from the Chase Bank was torn off. Trees were uprooted on Route 9 and West Farms Road, and at Ideal Plaza. The tornado caused roofing and siding damage to the building occupied by Ice Cream on Route 9. A fence and additional trees were downed on the property as well. The tornado dissipated shortly after.<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|July 25, 2016\n|EF1\n|[[Readington Township, New Jersey|Readington]]-[[Branchburg, New Jersey|Branchburg]], NJ\n|A 