lle in Mercer County. Numerous trees were felled, and several electric poles were damaged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://njwo.wordpress.com/2011/09/28/tornado-confirmed-near-robbinsville-in-mercer-county-new-jersey/|title=Tornado confirmed near Robbinsville in Mercer County New Jersey|last=njwo|date=2011-09-28|website=NJWO Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|August 9, 2011\n|EF0\n|[[Millstone, New Jersey|Millstone]], NJ\n|A brief tornado touched down in [[Millstone Township, New Jersey|Millstone Township]], and dissipated shortly after. No damage was reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/weather-guy/2011/08/tornado_confirmed_in_monmouth.html|title=Video: Tornado confirmed in Monmouth County|last=Stirling|first=Stephen|date=2011-08-12|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|September 16, 2010\n|EF1\n|[[Plumsted Township, New Jersey|Plumsted]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down in Plumsted Township, causing roof damage to two homes and downing numerous trees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2010/09/tornado_passed_through_ocean_c.html|title=National Weather Service confirms tornado touched down in N.J.|last=Associated|first=The|date=2010-09-17|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nynjpaweather.com/public/2010/09/17/tornado-confirmed-in-ocean-county-new-jersey/|title=Tornado Confirmed in Ocean County, New Jersey {{!}} {{!}} NY NJ PA Weather|date=2010-09-18|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|July 29, 2009\n|EF2\n|[[Sussex, New Jersey|Sussex]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down near Wantage in Sussex County, downing numerous trees, partially collapsing two barns and damaging several others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/phi/07292009|title=Confirmed Tornadoes in Monroe County, PA and Sussex County, NJ on 7/29/2009|last=US Department of Commerce|first=NOAA|website=www.weather.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2009/07/tornado_hits_sussex_county_tow.html|title=Tornado rips up trees, damages properties in Wantage Township|last=Drobness|first=Tanya|date=2009-07-31|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|July 27, 2004\n|F1\n|[[Pemberton, New Jersey|Pemberton]]-[[Woodland Park, New Jersey|Woodland]], NJ\n|A high end F1 tornado touched down in Pemberton Township in Burlington County, and then moved into Woodland Township. A roof was peeled off and the top floor of a building was damaged at the New Lisbon Developmental Center. Two workers in separate vans received minor injuries when one van was overturned and the other hit by a tree branch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/28/nyregion/two-hurt-after-tornado-hits-south-jersey.html|title=Two Hurt After Tornado Hits South Jersey|date=2004-07-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|May 27, 2001\n|F2\n|[[Manalapan Township, New Jersey|Manalapan]], NJ\n|A tornado touched down in the northeast corner of the Marlboro Airport and traveled northeast through Debracy Court and Hawkins Corner Road. Trees were downed, windows blown out and multiple homes received roof damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/29/nyregion/it-s-official-sunday-storm-in-new-jersey-was-a-tornado.html|title=It's Official: Sunday Storm In New Jersey Was a Tornado|last=Saulny|first=Susan|date=2001-05-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|}\nIn addition, tornadoes have been reported in New Jersey in 2006, 2004, 2003, 2001, 1999, 1995, 1994, 1983, and 1982. However, damage reports are not available.\n\n*October 27, 2003: Burlington County<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tornadoproject.com/alltorns/njtorn.htm|title=New Jersey Tornadoes|last=Grazulis|first=Doris and Tom|website=www.tornadoproject.com|access-date=April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n*September 23, 2003: Mercer County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*September 23, 2003: Hunterdon County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*September 23, 2003: Burlington County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*July 3, 2003: Cape May County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*May 27, 2001: Assessments of damage to buildings in Manalapan Township placed wind speed at 120 miles per hour, and determined that the twister was 200 feet wide and traveled a path of about a mile and a half.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/29/nyregion/it-s-official-sunday-storm-in-new-jersey-was-a-tornado.html|title=It's Official: Sunday Storm In New Jersey Was a Tornado|last=Saulny|first=Susan|date=May 29, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*August 20, 1999:Ocean County<ref name=\":0\"     />\n*February 12, 1999: Camden County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*July 16, 1995: Cape May County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*July 16, 1995: Cumberland County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*May 29, 1995: Burlington County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*August 2, 1994: Burlington County<ref name=\":0\" />\n*June 24, 1992: Washington Township tornado<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=New Jersey Tornado Damages 5 Homes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/25/nyregion/new-jersey-tornado-damages-5-homes.html |quote=A tornado touched down for 10 minutes last night in Washington Township, N.J., damaging five homes, knocking down several trees and cutting off power and phone service to more than a third of the town's 15,500 residents, the police said. No one was believed to have been injured in the storm, the police said. ...|newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=June 25, 1992 |accessdate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n*October 18, 1990: Montgomery Township tornado. Three homes were destroyed and 8 people were injured in [[Montgomery Township, New Jersey]]. Was rated an F3.\n*July 10, 1989: [[1989 Northeastern United States tornado outbreak|Northeastern United States tornado outbreak]]. Two F0s and an [[Fujita scale|F1]] tracked through parts of [[Passaic County, New Jersey]] and [[Bergen County, New Jersey]], snapping and uprooting trees, and causing $4&nbsp;million in damage. About 150 houses were damaged in Bergen county alone.<ref>{{cite news  | author= Constance L. Hayes | title = Unusually Fierce Winds Razed 100 Homes | url =https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/12/nyregion/unusually-fierce-winds-razed-100-homes.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | pages = B1-2 |quote=In northern New Jersey, damage was reported along a seven-mile swath from Ringwood to Wyckoff. The area is 20 miles west of Fort Lee, where a tornado was confirmed by the weather service. 'People saw a funnel cloud,' said Police Chief James O'Connor of Oakland, a town east of Ringwood that was affected. 'One man said the sound of the wind was like a locomotive passing through his living room.' In Wyckoff, 'windows in stores and houses literally exploded, and about 15 utility poles snapped right in half,' the coordinator of emergency management, Robert Shannon, said. No injuries were reported in Bergen or Passaic Counties. About 150 houses in Bergen were damaged, at a cost estimated at $2 million by an official of the county emergency management agency, Lieut. Edward C. Sturm. The damage in Passaic was also estimated at $2 million ...| date = July 12, 2007 | accessdate = October 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n* July 21, 1983: Ocean County, an F3 tornado that caused no fatalities or injuries.<ref name=\":0\"  />\n* June 29, 1982: Ocean County<ref name=\":0\"  />\n*May 28, 1973: Flanders County, a dozen homes were destroyed and 12 people were injured in [[Flanders, New Jersey]].<ref>[http://www.tornadoproject.com/alltorns/worstts.html]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was rated an [[Fujita scale|F3]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/19730528.34.5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 7, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003013/http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/19730528.34.5 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead|df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*August 1, 1899: Elizabeth County tornado <ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=A New Jersey Tornado. A Mighty Wind Creates Great Havoc in Elizabeth |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bvplAAAAIBAJ&sjid=g7wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2842,14304&dq=new+jersey+tornado&hl=en |quote=A tornado swept over this city yesterday afternoon, doing great damage. Houses, churches, factories and all buildings in the storm's path, which was three ... |newspaper=Camden Democrat |date=August 2, 1899 |accessdate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n*July 1, 1892: Gloucester County tornado<ref>[http://www3.gendisasters.com/new-jersey/14199/gloucester-nj-tornado-jun-1892 Gloucester, NJ tornado, Jun 1892 | GenDisasters ... Genealogy in Tragedy, Disasters, Fires, Floods<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Tornado in New Jersey |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1733202242.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+01%2C+1892&author=&pub=The+Sun+(1837-1985)&desc=TORNADO+IN+NEW+JERSEY&pqatl=google |quote=At 1.20 afternoon a wind-storm, with all the of [sic] a tornado, struck this city from the south- west, doing great damage to property ...\n |newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]] |date=July 1, 1892 |accessdate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n*June 29, 1835: [[1835 New Brunswick, New Jersey tornado|New Brunswick County tornado]]<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Dreadful Tornado |url=http://www3.gendisasters.com/new-jersey/6072/piscataway-nj-dreadful-tornado-june-1835 |quote=About 5 o'clock yesterday afternoon, a tornado passed over the town of Piscataway, about two miles from New Brunswick, which destroyed every house but two. ... |newspaper=New York Evening Star |date=June 20, 1835  |accessdate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of New Jersey hurricanes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://www.nj.com/news/2019/07/heres-all-the-tornadoes-that-hit-nj-over-50-years-including-5-twisters-in-2019.html\n* https://www.datawrapper.de/_/eK5yF/\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Jersey tornadoes}}\n[[Category:Tornadoes in New Jersey| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of tornadoes in the United States]]\n[[Category:New Jersey-related lists|Tornadoes]]\n", "name_user": "Csbull", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTornadoes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_New_Jersey_tornadoes"}
{"title_page": "Karaalio\u011flu Park", "text_new": "[[Image:Worker and Son monument on Antalya.JPG|thumb|Worker and Son monument in the park, sculpted by [[Mehmet Aksoy]]]]\n[[File:Hand sculpture in Karaalioglu Park.jpg|thumb|left|Hand sculpture]]\n'''Karaalio\u011flu Park''' ({{lang-tr|Karaalio\u011flu Park\u0131}}) is a large park in [[Antalya]], [[Turkey]]. It is just south of Kalei\u00e7i in the city center, easily reached on foot or by tram. The mayor's office, Municipal city theater, and an ancient fortress called [[H\u0131d\u0131rl\u0131k Tower]] overlooking the Roman harbor, view of the cliffs and the broad blue expanse of the [[Gulf of Antalya]] are major attractions of the park.\n\nUrban History museum is planning to the park as of mid 2000s.\n\nThere are the following monuments and statues in the park: the [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] monument at {{Coord|36|52|50.4|N|30|42|14.3|E}} which was created in 2010 on the 47th anniversary of the poet's death, the statue of Don Quixote at {{Coord|36|52|47.2|N|30|42|14.9|E}}, the Worker and Son monument at {{Coord|36|52|45.0|N|30|42|16.9|E}}, the Hand sculpture at {{Coord|36|52|41.5|N|30|42|20.6|E}} and the Frog sculptures at {{Coord|36|52|45.6|N|30|42|33.4|E}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Karaalioglu Park in Antalya, August 2017|url=https://independent-travellers.com/turkey/antalya/karaalioglu_park/|website=Independent Travellers|publisher=independent-travellers.com|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Antalya]]\n[[Category:Parks in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Geography of Antalya Province]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Worker and Son monument on Antalya.JPG|thumb|Worker and Son monument in the park, sculpted by [[Mehmet Aksoy]]]]\n[[File:Hand sculpture in Karaalioglu Park.jpg|thumb|left|Hand sculpture]]\n'''Karaalioglu Park''' ({{lang-tr|Karaalio\u011flu Park\u0131}}) is a large park in [[Antalya]], [[Turkey]]. It is just south of Kalei\u00e7i in the city center, easily reached on foot or by tram. The mayor's office, Municipal city theater, and an ancient fortress called [[H\u0131d\u0131rl\u0131k Tower]] overlooking the Roman harbor, view of the cliffs and the broad blue expanse of the [[Gulf of Antalya]] are major attractions of the park.\n\nUrban History museum is planning to the park as of mid 2000s.\n\nThere are the following monuments and statues in the park: the [[N\u00e2z\u0131m Hikmet]] monument at {{Coord|36|52|50.4|N|30|42|14.3|E}} which was created in 2010 on the 47th anniversary of the poet's death, the statue of Don Quixote at {{Coord|36|52|47.2|N|30|42|14.9|E}}, the Worker and Son monument at {{Coord|36|52|45.0|N|30|42|16.9|E}}, the Hand sculpture at {{Coord|36|52|41.5|N|30|42|20.6|E}} and the Frog sculptures at {{Coord|36|52|45.6|N|30|42|33.4|E}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Karaalioglu Park in Antalya, August 2017|url=https://independent-travellers.com/turkey/antalya/karaalioglu_park/|website=Independent Travellers|publisher=independent-travellers.com|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Antalya]]\n[[Category:Parks in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Geography of Antalya Province]]\n", "name_user": "Morris Schaffer", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karaalio%C4%9Flu_Park"}
{"title_page": "Siege of Newcastle", "text_new": "{{coord|54.972|-1.608|display=title|region:GB_scale:20000}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Newcastle\n|partof=the [[First English Civil War]]\n| image= Newcastle Castle, 1814.jpg\n| image_size = 150\n|caption=Newcastle Castle\n|date=3 February - 21 October 1644\n|place=[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n|result=Decisive [[Scotland|Scottish]] victory\n*Scottish occupation of Tyneside\n|combatant1=[[File:Scottish Covenanter Flag.svg|22px]] [[Covenanters]]\n|combatant2={{Flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|commander1=[[Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven|Earl of Leven]]<br>[[James Livingstone, 1st Earl of Callander|Earl of Callander]]\n|commander2=[[John Marlay (MP)|Governor Sir John Marlay]]\n|strength1=Six regiments\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|campaignbox=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Scottish Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Newcastle''' (3 February 1644 \u2013 21 October 1644) occurred during the [[First English Civil War]], when a   [[Covenanter]] army under the command of [[Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven|Lord General Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven]] besieged the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] garrison  under [[John Marlay (MP)|Sir John Marlay]], the city's governor. Eventually the Covenanters took the city of [[Newcastle-on-Tyne]] by storm, and the Royalist garrison who still held castle keep [[surrendered on terms]]. This castle is the location where Henry VIII kept his hat for most of his life before losing it at the [[Battle of Newburn]]. \n\nThis was not the first time that Newcastle-on-Tyne had changed hands during the [[Wars of the Three Kingdoms]]. The Scots had occupied the city during the [[Second Bishops\u2019 War]] in 1640.{{sfn|Murdoch|Grosjean|2014|pp=134-136}}\n\n==Invasion and siege==\nA Covenanter army from Scotland under the command of Lord General [[Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven| crossed into England in January 1644. As Leslie moved his army south he left six regiments under the direction of Lieutenant General [[James Livingstone, 1st Earl of Callander]], to lay siege to the city of [[Newcastle-on-Tyne]] beginning 3 February (after the town was formally asked to surrender){{sfn|Murdoch|Grosjean|2014|pp=134-136}}{{sfn|Lindsay}}{{sfn|Plant|2006}}\n\n==Battle of Marston Moor==\nThe city was not continually invested at that time. In a complicated situation, the Earl of Callander diverted his troops to take surrounding towns like [[Newburn]], as the main Covenanter army pressed south. In the meantime, the royalist governor reinforced his position and also sent forces south where the Royalist and the main Covenanter-Parliamentarian allied armies clashed at the [[Battle of Marston Moor]].{{sfn|Fraser|Emsley|1973|p=37}}\n\nThe defeat of the Royalist field army at [[Battle of Marston Moor|Marston Moor]] on 2 July ultimately decided the fate of Newcastle and all the other Royalist strongholds in the North East of England as all such garrisons would be separated from any possibility of relief during a siege.{{sfn|Lindsay}}{{sfn|Plant|2006}}\n\n==Bombardment, storming and surrender==\nFrom 15 August 1644 Newcastle and Tynemouth were again the main target for Callander, now joined by the main Covenanters under Leven. Bombardment and mines were necessary to breach the walls. The western half of the city's wall fell on 19 October 1644. Those remaining loyal to the Royalist cause retreated into the [[Newcastle Castle Keep|Castle Keep]]. Finding the situation hopeless,  surrender was negotiated with General Leslie by the Royalist  Governor,  Sir [[John Marlay (MP)|John Marlay]] on 21 October 1644. The terms of surrender were generous: the promise of mercy for the garrison was fulfilled, although some of the Royalist  leaders, including Marlay himself,  suffered imprisonment or banishment.{{sfn|Murdoch|Grosjean|2014|pp=134-136}}{{sfn|Fraser|Emsley|1973|p=37}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Covenanters were delighted at the result, more so it is thought than the English Parliament. Tynemouth had fallen on 27 October 1644 and the Scots were now able to control the Tyneside coal trade for a second time which they did until they were persuaded to leave on 30 January 1647 with the demise of the [[Solemn League and Covenant]].{{sfn|Fraser|Emsley|1973|p=37}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes}}\n::{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Fraser |first=C M |last2=Emsley |first2=K  |year=1973 |title=Tyneside |publisher=David & Charles |location=Newton Abbot}}\n::{{cite web |last1=Lindsay |first1=Euan |title=The Siege Of Newcastle 1644 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112142005/http://www.scotwars.com/battle_for_newcastle.htm |website=Wayback Machine |publisher=Internet Archive |accessdate=1 December 2011}}\n::{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Murdoch  |first=Steve  |last2=Grosjean |first2=Alexia |year=2014 |title=Alexander Leslie and the Scottish Generals of the Thirty Years' War, 1618-1648 |location=London }}\n::{{cite web|ref=harv |last=Plant |first=David |date=29 June 2006 |title=1644: Civil War in the North |website=British Civil Wars, Commonwealth & Protectorate 1638-1660|url=http://bcw-project.org/military/english-civil-war/northern-england/the-north-1644}}\n::{{cite book |last1=Serdiville |first1=Rosie |last2=Sadler |first2=John |title=The Great Siege of Newcastle 1644 |date=2011 |publisher=The History Press |location=Gloucestershire |isbn=978 0 7524 5989 9}}\n\n==External links==\n::{{cite book |title=Siege and Storm |first=Simon |last=Grennan |first2=Christopher |last2=Sperandio |year=2011|series=[http://kartoonkings.com/?p=495 Kartoon Kings]}} \u2014 A comic book about the siege.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newcastle-upon-Tyne, Siege of 1644}}\n[[Category:History of Newcastle upon Tyne|Siege]]\n[[Category:First English Civil War]]\n[[Category:Wars of the Three Kingdoms]]\n[[Category:1644 in England]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1644]]\n[[Category:Military history of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving Scotland]]\n[[Category:17th century in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Sieges of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Massacres during the Wars of the Three Kingdoms]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|54.972|-1.608|display=title|region:GB_scale:20000}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Siege of Newcastle\n|partof=the [[First English Civil War]]\n| image= Newcastle Castle, 1814.jpg\n| image_size = 150\n|caption=Newcastle Castle\n|date=3 February - 21 October 1644\n|place=[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n|result=Decisive [[Scotland|Scottish]] victory\n*Scottish occupation of Tyneside\n|combatant1=[[File:Scottish Covenanter Flag.svg|22px]] [[Covenanters]]\n|combatant2={{Flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n|commander1=[[Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven|Earl of Leven]]<br>[[James Livingstone, 1st Earl of Callander|Earl of Callander]]\n|commander2=[[John Marlay (MP)|Governor Sir John Marlay]]\n|strength1=Six regiments\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n|campaignbox=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Scottish Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\n\nThe '''Siege of Newcastle''' (3 February 1644 \u2013 21 October 1644) occurred during the [[First English Civil War]], when a   [[Covenanter]] army under the command of [[Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven|Lord General Alexander Leslie, 1st Earl of Leven]] besieged the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] garrison  under [[John Marlay (MP)|Sir John Marlay]], the city's governor. Eventually the Covenanters took the city of [[Newcastle-on-Tyne]] by storm, and the Royalist garrison who still held castle keep [[surrendered on terms]]. This castle is the location where Henry VIII